The '''2014 May Day protests''' were a series of international protests involving millions of people that took place worldwide on May Day (1 May 2014) over the ongoing [[Great Recession|global economic crisis]] including austerity measures and poor working conditions.

== Africa ==

=== Morocco ===
Tens of thousands of Moroccans marched demanding better wages and condemning a new 10 percent salary hike to the minimum wage in the private sector as insufficient.<ref name="Cairo" />

== Asia ==

=== Armenia ===
Several hundred people from the [[Armenian Communist Party|Communist Party of Armenia]] held a rally in [[Yerevan]] demonstrating in favor of Armenia's accession to the [[Customs Union]] created by Belarus, Kazakhstan and Russia. The people marched towards the Russian Embassy, carrying Soviet-era flags and placards and chanting "Russia, Russia!".<ref name="RT" />

=== Bangladesh ===
Thousands of workers in Bangladesh, including many from garment factories, took to the streets demanding the execution for the owner of a [[2013 Savar building collapse|building that collapsed]] last year, killing more than 1,100 laborers in the worst disaster the garment industry has seen.<ref name="AP">{{cite news |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/may-day-rallies-demand-reform-5-hurt-cambodia |title=May Day rallies demand reform; 5 hurt in Cambodia |newspaper=Associated Press |date=1 May 2014}}</ref>

=== Cambodia ===
Nearly 1,000 factory workers and supporters of the opposition Cambodia National Rescue Party gathered outside the [[Phnom Penh]]'s Freedom Park, which had been sealed off with barbed wire with hundreds of police on guard.<ref name="AP" /> At least five people were injured after security forces armed with sticks and batons turned on protesters.<ref name="Aljazeera" />

=== Hong Kong ===
According to organisers, up to 5,000 workers in Hong Kong joined the Labor Day march, calling for improved working conditions and for the government to restrict the number of working hours.<ref name="AP" /><ref name="Aljazeera">{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/europe/2014/05/protests-mark-may-day-around-world-20145183733534514.html |title=Protests mark May Day around the world |newspaper=Aljazeera |date=1 May 2014}}</ref>

=== Indonesia ===
A major protest was held in [[Jakarta]], where 33,000 people marched peacefully through the city centre. According to Rikwanto, police spokesman, 18,000 police officers were deployed on the streets to avoid conflicts.<ref name="Aljazeera" />

=== Iran ===
Iranian President [[Hassan Rouhani]] told thousands of laborers gathered to celebrate [[International Workers' Day]] in the capital, [[Tehran]], that he supports the establishment of unions "free of any interference by the state".<ref name="AP" />

=== Iraq ===
Dozens of people, mostly members of the [[Iraqi Communist Party]], held a rally near the party headquarters in downtown [[Baghdad]], raising Iraqi flags and those of the former Soviet Union.<ref name="AP" />

=== Malaysia ===
{{Main|May Day anti-GST rally 2014}}
Thousands of Malaysians held a peaceful protest on the streets of Dataran Merdeka, in downtown [[Kuala Lumpur]], against a looming goods and services tax that they fear will increase the cost of living.<ref name="AP" /> During the protest were reported several minor scuffles started by fringe youth groups.<ref name="Guardian">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/01/may-day-rallies-around-the-world-live-updates |title=Tear gas fired in Istanbul as May Day rallies held around world |newspaper=The Guardian |author=Mark Tran |date=1 May 2014}}</ref>

=== Philippines ===
In the Philippines, thousands of workers marched peacefully in [[Manila]] to protest low wages and employers' practice of replacing regular employees with temporary hires who get low pay and little or no benefits. They also decried what they said was the failure of President [[Benigno Aquino III]] to deliver on his anti-corruption and pro-poor reforms.<ref name="AP" />

=== Taiwan ===
More than 10,000 workers marched to the labor ministry in Taiwan's capital [[Taipei]] demanding wage hikes and a ban on companies hiring cheap temporary or part-time workers.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/turkish-police-clash-with-may-day-protesters/ |title=Turkish police clash with May Day protesters |newspaper=The Times of Israel |date=1 April 2014}}</ref>

=== Turkey ===
Police intervened with [[water cannon]]s and [[tear gas]] to disperse hundreds of demonstrators that tried to defy the interdiction to meet on 1 May in [[Taksim Square]], [[Istanbul]], emblematic for anti-government protests in Turkey.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27234646 |title=Turkey May Day protests hit by tear gas near Taksim Square |newspaper=BBC News |date=1 May 2014}}</ref> Riot police assaulted, using vehicles equipped with water cannons, demonstrators who tried to force the barrages in [[Beşiktaş|Beşiktaş district]] to reach the neighboring Taksim Square.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailysabah.com/nation/2014/05/01/demonstrators-insisting-on-taksim-clash-with-police |title=Demonstrators insisting on Taksim clash with police |newspaper=Daily Sabah |date=1 May 2014}}</ref> Areas around the European centre of Turkish metropolis were transformed into fortified camp and tens of thousands of police officers – up to 40,000 according to Turkish media – were mobilized to prevent access.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Middle-East/2014/Apr-30/254962-thousands-to-defy-may-day-ban-on-turkeys-taksim-square.ashx#axzz30SdnLPU6 |title=Thousands to defy May Day ban on Turkey's Taksim Square |newspaper=The Daily Star |author=Dilay Gundogan |date=1 May 2014}}</ref> According to the Istanbul Governor's Office, at least 142 protesters have been detained by police and 90 people, 19 of whom are police officers, have been injured during the protests.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://rt.com/news/156124-turkey-protests-gas-cannon/ |title=Turkish police clash with May Day protesters in Istanbul |newspaper=RT |date=1 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/05/01/us-turkey-protests-idUSBREA4005520140501 |title=Riot police clash with May Day protesters in Istanbul |newspaper=Reuters |author=Ayla Jean Yackley, Evrim Ergin |date=1 May 2014}}</ref> Similar demonstrations took place in more than 30 [[provinces of Turkey]], including the capital [[Ankara]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/live-police-use-water-cannons-tear-gas-and-rubber-bullets-in-istanbuls-tense-may-day.aspx?pageID=238&nID=65820&NewsCatID=339 |title=Police use water cannons, tear gas and rubber bullets in Istanbul's tense May Day |newspaper=Hürriyet Daily News |date=1 May 2014}}</ref>

== Europe ==

=== France ===
According to authorities, nearly 100,000 people attended the Labor Day rallies in France, with the biggest rallies in Paris and other major cities such as [[Bordeaux]] and [[Toulouse]]. The demonstrations targeted the savings plan of 50 billion euros announced by Prime Minister [[Manuel Valls]].<ref name="Aljazeera" />

=== Greece ===
Nearly 20,000 Greeks marked May Day by demonstrating against government reforms which they say have hurt workers through layoffs and wage cuts.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.euronews.com/2014/05/01/greek-workers-turn-out-on-may-day-to-protest-against-reforms-and-austerity/ |title=Greek workers use May Day to protest against reforms and austerity |newspaper=Euronews |date=1 May 2014}}</ref>

=== Italy ===
In Italy's [[Turin]], scuffles broke out between police and hundreds of protesters. Activists lobbed smoke bombs at police, who charged demonstrators in the northern industrial city, which has been badly hit by a painful two-year recession. It was less violent in Rome, where 300,000 people packed into a huge, free May Day concert organized by trade unions.<ref name="Cairo">{{cite news |url=http://thecairopost.com/news/108874/news/tear-gas-at-turkish-may-day-protests-red-square-rally-draws-100000 |title=Tear gas at Turkish May Day protests, Red Square rally draws 100,000 |newspaper=The Cairo Post |date=1 May 2014}}</ref> Thousands of people also took part in a peaceful demonstration called by the main trade unions in [[Pordenone]], near [[Venice]], where the closure of a nearby washing machine plant owned by Sweden's [[Electrolux]] has put 1,300 jobs at risk.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nst.com.my/latest/thousands-protest-against-unemployment-in-italy-1.584503 |title=Thousands protest against unemployment in Italy |newspaper=New Straits Times |date=1 May 2014}}</ref>

=== Russia ===
[[File:Antiwar Democratic March in St. Petersburg on 1 May 2014 (100 3492).JPG|thumb|200px|In [[Saint Petersburg]], the May Day rally turned into a protest against [[2014 Russian military intervention in Ukraine|Russian military intervention in Ukraine]].]]
Over 100,000 attended a protest march from the [[Red Square]] to the [[State Historical Museum]] in Moscow, reviving a tradition last seen before the [[collapse of the Soviet Union]] in 1991.<ref name="Aljazeera" /> The event was organized by the Federation of Independent Trade Unions of Russia.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://voiceofrussia.com/news/2014_05_01/photo-Over-100-000-people-taking-part-in-May-Day-unions-demonstration-in-central-Moscow-6968/ |title=Over 100,000 people taking part in May Day unions demonstration in central Moscow |newspaper=The Voice of Russia |date=1 May 2014}}</ref> Labour union organisers said that a total of 2 million people had attended similar rallies around the country.<ref name="Guardian" />

=== Serbia ===
Various labour groups staged a protest in [[Belgrade]] in order to voice their concern over the expected austerity measures announced by Serbia's new government.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://o.canada.com/news/photos-may-day-and-international-labour-day |title=Photos: May Day and International Labour Day |newspaper=Canada.com |date=1 May 2014}}</ref>

=== Spain ===
Rallies were held in more than 70 Spanish cities. In [[Madrid]], thousands marched through the city centre, waving signs demanding an end to austerity measure and criticising the government over a perceived lack of focus on job creation.

=== Switzerland ===
In Switzerland's financial capital [[Zurich]], about 14,000 people turned out in support of a move to fix the minimum wage at 4,000 [[Swiss franc]]s ($4,500, €3,300) which will be put to a referendum this month.<ref name="Cairo" />

=== Ukraine ===
[[File:RussianSpringOdessa1stMay2014 03.JPG|thumb|200px|May Day demonstration in [[Odessa]]]]
In [[Odessa]], May Day rallies have turned into anti-government protests. Clashes have broken out between protesters and police in [[Donetsk]] as separatists attempted to storm the prosecutor's office.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1252895/ukraine-may-day-protesters-fight-with-police |title=Ukraine May Day Protesters Fight With Police |newspaper=Sky News |date=1 May 2014}}</ref>

Over 30,000 demonstrators took to the streets in [[Simferopol]], the capital of the [[Crimean peninsula]], for the annual Labor Day rally. Following [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|Crimea's accession to Russia]], this is the first time 1 May has proceeded with people waving Russian flags and shouting "Russian and Crimea together forever".<ref name="RT">{{cite news |url=http://rt.com/news/156084-may-day-protest-violence/ |title=Labor rallies around the globe as world celebrates May Day |newspaper=RT |date=1 May 2014}}</ref>

=== United Kingdom ===
Thousands of activists attended a May Day rally in honour of veteran political campaigner [[Tony Benn]] and rail union leader [[Bob Crow]] who died within days of each other in March.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/may-day-activists-in-london-honour-bob-crow-and-tony-benn-as-international-workers-day-protests-turn-violent-in-turkey-and-cambodia-9310844.html |title=May Day: Activists in London honour Bob Crow and Tony Benn as International Workers' Day protests turn violent in Turkey and Cambodia |newspaper=The Independent |author=Rob Williams |date=1 May 2014}}</ref>

== North America ==

=== United States ===
Thousands of community advocates and immigrant rights supporters marched for worker rights and immigrant justice in downtown Los Angeles. Three different May Day marches were planned by three different groups. As a result of the marches, some downtown streets were closed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/May-Day-Protests-Marches-Downtown-Los-Angeles-Immigration-Reform-Workers-Rights-257479671.html |title=Thousands Expected to Attend Downtown LA May Day Marches |newspaper=NBC Southern California |author=Samia Khan, Toni Guinyard |date=1 May 2014}}</ref>
